	<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-123led bypostauthor even depth-2 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-22">
		<article id="comment-22" class="comment">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/86b77e4f66a277fad74763ee5dcdb2d4?s=39&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-39' height='39' width='39' /><span class="fn">123led</span> on <a href="http://123led.wordpress.com/about/#comment-22"><time datetime="2011-01-09T01:19:01+00:00">January 9, 2011 at 01:19</time></a> <span class="says">said:</span>
									</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

				
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>Hi,</p>
<p>The Sure display based on the 1632 suffers from getting very dim when a lot of the LED&#8217;s are on, whereas their board based on the 1632C doesn&#8217;t have this problem. As far as I know it&#8217;s because the 1632 needs additional driver circuitry which Sure didn&#8217;t implement. The newer 1632C has it built in. </p>
<p>Nick</p>
</div>

			<div class="reply">
				<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/about/?replytocom=22#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-22", "22", "respond", "2")'>Reply <span>&darr;</span></a>			</div><!-- .reply -->
