		<article id="comment-102" class="comment">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/86b77e4f66a277fad74763ee5dcdb2d4?s=39&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-39' height='39' width='39' /><span class="fn">Nick</span> on <a href="http://123led.wordpress.com/about/#comment-102"><time datetime="2011-04-04T07:26:41+00:00">April 4, 2011 at 07:26</time></a> <span class="says">said:</span>
									</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

				
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>You&#8217;d need to wire them up to 4 spare input pins, then re work the code so it moves the correct paddle up or down, plus you would need to change the scoring, and either strip out all the other clock stuff or add another &#8216;Game&#8217; mode. I.e. it&#8217;s quite a bit of work!</p>
</div>

