	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-2205">
		<article id="comment-2205" class="comment">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/f1cc04d3d2bd3e2529ca98cfc209bd56?s=68&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-68' height='68' width='68' /><span class="fn">Eric Dugas</span> on <a href="http://123led.wordpress.com/about/#comment-2205"><time datetime="2011-12-10T18:09:16+00:00">December 10, 2011 at 18:09</time></a> <span class="says">said:</span>
									</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

				
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>Hi, have you tried in setup:</p>
<p>pinMode(x pin, OUTPUT);<br />
pinMode(x pin, OUTPUT);</p>
<p>then in loop:</p>
<p> digitalWrite(x pin, LOW);<br />
 digitalWrite(x pin, HIGH);</p>
<p>That is what I did in the RTC code as I needed to use Arduino pin 16 LOW (0v) and pin 17 HIGH (5V)</p>
<p>just a thought! again I might be really off the track here!!</p>
<p>Cheers</p>
<p>Eric</p>
</div>

