	<li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-5398">
		<article id="comment-5398" class="comment">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/1d6847c8f04c7e618cf3423075655591?s=68&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-68' height='68' width='68' /><span class="fn">Tim</span> on <a href="http://123led.wordpress.com/about/#comment-5398"><time datetime="2012-03-30T16:29:02+00:00">March 30, 2012 at 16:29</time></a> <span class="says">said:</span>
									</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

				
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>Problem solved. I was running the project on a dual voltage output supply. I switched the displays and arduino stand-alone board to one supply and it works great. Must have been a difference in supply grounds or the project not resetting correctly.</p>
</div>

			<div class="reply">
				<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/about/?replytocom=5398#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-5398", "5398", "respond", "2")'>Reply <span>&darr;</span></a>			</div><!-- .reply -->
