		<article id="comment-13628" class="comment">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/86b77e4f66a277fad74763ee5dcdb2d4?s=39&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-39' height='39' width='39' /><span class="fn">Nick</span> on <a href="http://123led.wordpress.com/about/#comment-13628"><time datetime="2013-01-11T19:40:49+00:00">January 11, 2013 at 19:40</time></a> <span class="says">said:</span>
									</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

				
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>Yes you should see half the clock with just one board. Changing the dip switch will choose which half.</p>
<p>Check the dip switches and check all the connections and that you have everything wired to the correct pins. Also check the clock is ticking, the arduino pin 13 LED should flash once a second.</p>
<p>Also check you have the new version of the display board with the chips on the back.</p>
</div>

